# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>The Quixote-class frigate was constructed by Eaton Aerospace of Inglesmond for the Terran Hegemony Navy beginning in 2350. Conceived during a period of ambitious naval expansion, the class earned an infamous reputation as one of the Hegemony's most troubled procurement programs. A design intended as a battlecruiser was reclassified midway through development after cost-cutting measures left the vessel underpowered for its intended role, and questionable decisions within the Procurement Department compounded the embarrassment. Redesignated as a missile frigate and armed to match, the Quixote overcame its difficult birth to serve as a capable convoy escort for nearly two centuries. The class ultimately proved more adaptable than its critics expected, finding continued relevance long after the Hegemony Navy moved on to newer designs.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Displacing 780,000 tons across 715 meters of hull, the Quixote carries the heaviest missile armament of any Star League-era frigate. Eighteen Killer Whale launchers form the backbone of the weapons suite, with six mounted in the nose and paired launchers covering every other arc. Twenty-four White Shark and twenty-four Barracuda capital missile launchers supplement the Killer Whales, creating overlapping fields of missile fire that made the Quixote lethal to anything within range. Two NAC/30 naval autocannons and six NL55 naval lasers provide additional firepower at closer ranges. One thousand one hundred seventy-seven single heat sinks manage the thermal output.</p><p>Nearly 1,200 tons of improved ferro-aluminum armor give the frigate protection exceeding most heavy cruisers. Six docking collars support a substantial transport capacity, complemented by twelve fighter bays, six small craft bays, and over 176,000 tons of cargo space. Three gravity decks, the largest pair measuring 145 meters in diameter, serve a crew of over 480 personnel including 150 marines. Safe thrust of two and maximum thrust of three reflect the undersized drives inherited from the Lola-class destroyer, the critical weakness that ultimately doomed the design to early replacement by the faster Congress-class.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The most remarkable individual Quixote is the vessel known successively as TCS Vendetta, CPS Redemption, and RSS Redemption. Originally a mothballed Star League-era hull, the Word of Blake refurbished the vessel and gifted it to the Taurian Concordat in 3074. As TCS Vendetta, it became the centerpiece of Taurian retaliatory strikes during the Jihad, conducting orbital bombardments across multiple Federated Suns worlds including Warren, Keuterville, and New Syrtis. At Brusett in 3075, the Vendetta engaged and destroyed the FCS Kathil before being forced to retreat. After hitting a minefield at Firgrove in 3080, the damaged vessel was transferred to the Calderon Protectorate by treaty in 3081 and renamed CPS Redemption, serving as the only active WarShip in the Periphery. Decades later, as RSS Redemption under the Republic of the Sphere, the ancient frigate participated in Task Force Walkure during the ilClan crisis, firing every available battery at the Jade Falcon Blue Talon before ramming it in a final act of defiance.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Quixote-class frigate entered service with the Terran Hegemony Navy in 2350 under circumstances that would become legendary for all the wrong reasons. The vessel was originally conceived as a battlecruiser, but the Hegemony reclassified it as a frigate during the design process. Engineers attempting to reduce costs reused the drive systems from the smaller Lola-class destroyer, a critical miscalculation that left the vessel woefully underpowered for its considerable displacement. Compounding the design failure, a bureaucrat in the Procurement Department authorized two hundred fifty hulls for production. Later evidence suggested this was a deliberate act to circumvent Admiralty objections and curb naval spending at a time when resources were slim.</p><p>The Admiralty, stuck with a vessel too slow for its original role, adapted by redesignating it as a missile frigate and loading it with the heaviest missile batteries available. Armed accordingly, the Quixote found an effective niche as a convoy escort. Farragut and Monsoon battleships welcomed the substantial fire support the class provided, and its heavy armor protection allowed it to absorb punishment that would cripple lighter escorts. For nearly two centuries the class served capably in this role despite its sluggish acceleration.</p><p>By 2536, Hegemony admirals concluded the Quixote had outlived its usefulness, as incidents demonstrated it could be outmaneuvered by virtually any foreign-built vessel of comparable size. A year later, Dekirk Aerospace submitted the Congress-class frigate design as a replacement, and the Quixotes were gradually retired to mothball yards. Beginning in 2709, the mothballed hulls were reactivated and converted into the Volga-class transport, with the Quixote's undersized drives proving ideally suited for a slower cargo vessel.</p><p>At least one Quixote accompanied General Kerensky's Exodus fleet, and during Operation Klondike a spacefarer-operated vessel at Circe's zenith point escaped Clan forces amid a desperate running battle. While the accompanying Potemkin was captured two weeks later, the Quixote was never seen again. The class returned to prominence centuries later during the Jihad, when a refurbished hull entered Taurian Concordat service and went on to pass through three nations before meeting its end in the ilClan era.</p>
</history>

